  "issue_title": "[BUG] Mirror outage drops cached mirror PRs for miners with mixed legacy and mirror contributions",
  "issue_body": "## Description\n\nWhen `mirror.gittensor.io` is unavailable, miners with both legacy GitHub contributions and mirror-backed contributions can be evaluated using only their fresh legacy PRs.\n\nThe mirror fetch failure is folded into the general `github_pr_fetch_failed` flag. Cache fallback then checks `should_use_cache_fallback`, which only returns true when `github_pr_fetch_failed` is true and `total_prs == 0`.\n\nFor mixed-source miners, the legacy GitHub fetch can still succeed and produce one or more PRs. That makes `total_prs > 0`, so the validator treats the result as a partial legacy fetch and skips cache fallback. Since the mirror fetch failed atomically, all mirror PR lists are empty for that round.\n\nThis silently drops valid cached mirror contributions from the evaluation. In practice, that can reduce or zero a miner's OSS reward, especially if the missing mirror PRs are needed to satisfy the minimum valid merged PR threshold.\n\n## Steps to Reproduce\n\n1. Start with a miner that has a cached successful evaluation containing both:\n   - legacy GitHub PRs\n   - mirror-backed PRs from mirror-enabled repositories\n2. Simulate a mirror outage by making the mirror fetch fail, for example by having the mirror client raise a `MirrorRequestError`.\n3. Let the legacy GitHub fetch succeed for the same miner and return at least one PR.\n4. Run validator cache handling.\n5. Observe that cache fallback is skipped because `total_prs > 0`.\n6. Observe that the miner is finalized with only the fresh legacy PRs and no mirror PRs.\n\n## Expected Behavior\n\nThe validator should distinguish mirror-source fetch failures from legacy GitHub partial-fetch failures.\n\nWhen the mirror source fails but legacy GitHub data is fresh, the validator should not discard the miner's cached mirror contributions. If a cached evaluation exists, the validator should keep the fresh legacy PRs and restore the cached mirror PRs into the current evaluation before final scoring.\n\nExisting behavior should remain unchanged for:\n- full-fetch failures where no PRs were loaded\n- legacy partial-pagination failures\n- cases where no cached evaluation is available\n\n## Actual Behavior\n\nThe mirror failure is treated like a generic GitHub fetch failure, but cache fallback is blocked because the successful legacy fetch makes `total_prs > 0`.\n\nThe validator finalizes a partial legacy-only evaluation with empty mirror PR lists. Cached mirror contributions are not restored, so the miner's reward can be incorrectly reduced or zeroed during a mirror outage.\n\n## Environment\n\n- OS: Linux x86_64, kernel `6.8.0-90-generic`\n- Python version: Python 3.12.3\n- Commit/Version: `gittensor` 5.0.0, `test` branch at `34ffeb8c4b1167a8c556e3a813901613dbd7d8dc`\n\n## Additional Context\n\nRelevant code paths:\n\n- `gittensor/validator/oss_contributions/mirror/combine.py`\n- `gittensor/classes.py`\n- `neurons/validator.py`\n- `gittensor/validator/oss_contributions/reward.py`\n\nThe root issue is that mirror fetch failure and legacy GitHub fetch failure are collapsed into one flag, but they need different cache fallback behavior. A source-specific mirror fetch-failure signal would let the validator restore cached mirror PRs without changing the legacy partial-fetch semantics.\n",
  "merged_at": "2026-05-01T22:54:55.000Z",
